Singapore Stocks: Hsu Fu Chi International, Noble, Tiger Air

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-09-27T04:04:11Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-27/singapore-stocks-hsu-fu-chi-international-noble-tiger-air.html
Singapore ’s Straits Times Index
gained 1.4 percent to 2,690.82 as of noon local time, heading
for its first advance in four days. All but four stocks rose in
the index of 30 companies.  The following shares were among the most active in the
market. Stock symbols are in parentheses after the company name.  Commodity suppliers: The Thomson Reuters/Jefferies CRB
Index, which tracks prices of 19 commodities from copper to corn,
gained 0.4 percent in  New York  yesterday, its first advance in
four days.  Noble Group Ltd. (NOBL)  , a Hong Kong-based supplier of
energy, food and mining commodities, rose 1.5 percent to S$1.40.
 Olam International Ltd. (OLAM)  , a Singapore-based supplier of
agricultural commodities, increased 4 percent to S$2.36.  Hsu Fu Chi International Ltd. (HFCI)  , a China-based
snack and candy maker, gained 2 percent to S$4.08. The company
said shareholders approved the proposed acquisition by Nestle SA,
the world’s largest food company, of a 60 percent stake in the
company. Nestle in July offered S$2.07 billion ($1.6 billion),
or S$4.35 a share, for the stake.  Tiger Airways Holdings Ltd. (TGR)  , a budget carrier
partly owned by Singapore Airlines Ltd. (SIA SP), added 0.6
percent to 82.5 Singapore cents. The company said it added two
new Airbus A320-232 planes, expanding its fleet to 20 aircraft.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in Singapore at 
